events.name: Nicholas Carl Roberts Shares his Llama App
events.description:
Nicholas Carl Roberts' Story

I'm a computer science student at Fresno City College. I started programming in 2011 while I was in a high school program that involved learning about web technologies and website development. I branched off on my own during that time to learn as much as I could about other programming languages because I felt that knowing just one thing wouldn't be enough. My interest progressed as I took college classes in computer science, and eventually I took an Android app development course at Fresno City in 2014. I taught myself a lot of extra stuff regarding app development and using other technologies in conjunction with it, such as other APIs. I'm currently the teacher's assistant and tutor for the current iteration of the Android app development course at FCC. On the other hand I also really enjoy the theoretical aspect of computer science and the more mathematical side of things, and I think that because of this, I someday want to pursue computer science research. I hope to transfer to UCLA or UC Berkeley in the Fall if I'm accepted into their programs. 

Historical information regarding my app:

Version 1.0 of my app was the product of a suggestion from one of my friends to create an app to rival the infamous "Muffin Button" (I don't actually know if it's infamous). My app had, for the most part, graphics and colors that were meant to be temporary. However after I had written it I thought that it would be funny to leave it as it is and just publish it, the first reason being that I kind of liked the lo-fi feel of it since it was already an essentially useless app, and secondly because I didn't want to look at it any more. After receiving a low review on the Play Store and my number of installs had dropped significantly, I realized that I needed to do something raise my app standards. I made the app look much nicer than it did previously, and I added features such as being able to download quantum random coordinates from the Australian National University's Quantum Optics lab. The work put into this aspect was justifiable mostly because the only llama related thing funnier than a lo-fi llama button app is a completely overpowered llama app that actually uses cutting edge research (I wasn't sure that the llamas were 'random' enough). I also did it because I wanted an excuse to use the ANU Quantum Optics random number generator APIs that people on GitHub had written.

events.name: Project Tango
events.description:
Our Guest Speaker: Justin Ribeiro

Engineer and show runner at Stickman Ventures. Co-organizer of the GDG Oakdale, Oakdale OpenMesh, and his three daughters. 18 years building software, hacking on sensors, and making the web better. Currently speaking, teaching and sometimes breaking the latest in wearable technology.
Recently minted Google Developer Expert in Wearables https://developers.google.com/experts/+JustinRibeiro

Justin is Awesome!

What is Project Tango? The goal of Project Tango is to give mobile devices a human-scale understanding of space and motion. Project Tango provides unique sensing capabilities that allow developers to explore new user experiences not possible on other mobile devices. It's more than just another touch screen app.

Developing for Project Tango

Developing for Tango is a lot like developing for your typical phone. You have Android and Android Studio, support libs...the usual tools of the trade. That however is where the differences end.

In this talk we'll explore some of the sensors and APIs that Tango has that the current crop of devices do not, and we'll see just how to build some amazing applications.

events.name: Todd McLeod Presents Go Lang
events.description: Go is an open source programming language that makes it easy to build simple, reliable, and efficient software. Go provides the ability for "server-side" programming. Traditional choices for server-side languages have included PHP, ASP, and JSP. Increasingly popular server-side programming languages include Ruby, Python, and Node.js. While there are advantages and disadvantages to all languages, no server-side language is going to be faster than "Go." Couple the speed of Go with Google App Engine and Cloud Storage, and you are now using the exact same architecture as Google. This means that your web apps are going to be incredibly fast and will easily scale to millions of users. Go is an amazing choice for a server-side language as it was developed by some of the same individuals who created the C programming language, one of the most influential programming languages of all time. Robert Griesemer, Rob Pike, and Ken Thompson created Go to be a modern language that easily uses multiple cores, easily implements concurrency, easily works in distributed environments, and easily allows the programmer to write programs - it has a very lean and user-friendly syntax! Come learn about one of the most awesome and exciting languages ever created. You will leave with resources and code samples to start making all of your software and apps really go.…

events.name: LineageOS: Compile your own Android derivative to your phone
events.description:
- Do you have an old phone and you didn't receive updates for a long time now but you'd like to have latest Android versions?
- Maybe you didn't receive too many (or any) updates even from the get-go for your new phone but you want to stay updated?
- Would you like to get rid of phone provider's crap and have a clean OS?
- Are you concerned about security vulnerabilities and you'd prefer to not wait until patches go through both the phone manufacturers and the phone provider's slow pipeline?
- Maybe you bought some shiny phone like Pixel XL but you are thinking what will you do when Google 2 year software update policy runs out for your device

A possible solution is to compile your own Android OS. You don't have to be a computer scientist to do that fortunately. Our presenter from Europe is a living example for that. He'll demonstrate how someone can compile LineageOS to cell phones. LineageOS is a continuation of CyanogenMod. This session will contain live demonstration, Linux command line and more.

Speaker: Attila Toth

Bio: Attila Toth is a medical doctor who has deeper knowledge in open source software technologies than most full-time software engineers. His first Linux experience was with Slackware (1995), then for a long time he was Debian enthusiast also including Adamantix (Trusted Debian -  a hardened/secured version). He is very security savvy which led him to convert to Gentoo in 2003, more specifically Hardened Gentoo (an extremely secured version of Gentoo) from the beginning. Attila is a Grsecurity believer since the early days.

His daytime profession is radiologist at the Semmelweis University's Heart and Vascular Center, specialty: cardiac MR, congenital heart disease. MRI radiology requires good technology skills. One of his interests are pulse programming (programming the MRI machine's running sequence; involves vendor provided proprietary environments, NDA mandatory). Language skills: C, C++, Asm. Commit he is most proud of: making cpuid PIC-aware (Position Independent Code aware) in Intel's cpuid by altering some Assembly code.

Hobbies: flatwater kayaking, running.

We tried to find a good date & time between the timezone differences and scheduling constraints. Hopefully this meetup will be a delicious food for your brain before the actual Saturday lunch.

Liability: flashing your custom ROM onto a phone requires rooting and unlocking. Steps can potentially brick your phone, you can loose data and void your warranty. We are not responsible if such event happens.

events.name: Security, In app purchases, e-commerce
events.description:
I'm not a fan of money in general, but there comes a time in every software engineer's life when they have to deal with purchases, and that's when the game gets *real*, because it directly connects to your customers' money so your reputation is on the line. Not to mention your own wealth and sanity (if you leave a security hole you can easily become bankrupt). I'll tell you an interesting story about Android In-App purchases. Along the way you'll learn important security principals of in-app purchases and e-commerce in general.
This won't be any kind of marketing presentation: you will hear fair amount of criticism and frustration.
We'll have accompanying source code again.

events.name: Using Story to Design Digital Products
events.description:
There are many ways to start designing a digital product. If you are a newcomer, you might be tempted to jump straight into using a graphic design tool, like Sketch or Photoshop. However, there is a high possibility that this path will lead you to do work that is unnecessary. Or, even worse, lead you to design a product that users don’t want. So, what are your options then? Here’s an idea…How about taking a more holistic approach and starting with the story? In her book, The User’s Journey: Storymapping Products that People Love, Donna Lichaw highlights how important the use of story is when designing a new or existing product. She goes on to outline three important techniques: the concept story, the origin story, and the usage story. This talk is an overview of how she describes story when it's applied to product design. It will also walk you through how to use those three techniques with a custom-made example.

Joshwin Greene is a long-time member of GDG Fresno and WTM Fresno. He graduated with a degree in Software Engineering from UC Irvine in 2016. He is also a Fresno City College alumni. He is both a product designer and a software developer. He currently works as a contractor where he designs and develops mobile & web applications.

events.name: GDG Monthly meetup
events.description:
We will do a codelab for our next GDG/WTM Meeting.

In this codelab, you will learn how to build a simple "teachable machine", a custom image classifier that you will train on the fly in the browser using TensorFlow.js, a powerful and flexible machine learning library for Javascript. You will first load and run a popular pre-trained model called MobileNet for image classification in the browser. You will then use a technique called "transfer learning", which bootstraps our training with the pre-trained MobileNet model and customizes it to train for your application.

Anna and Rio give you a quick overview of the code lab and show you the ending project output! Bring your own device and let's get coding!

We're in room 5!

events.name: Next '19 Extended Fresno
events.description:
This event will commemorate the global Cloud Next 19 event (https://cloud.withgoogle.com/next/sf/) held in San Francisco on the same week. That event is everything about cloud (IaaS or PaaS level, orchestrating machines in the cloud, big data, machine learning, and deep learning). We'll have several options to go based on how many attend and what are the needs, beginners are welcome!

For beginners we have a slide deck which introduces Google Cloud Platform and its parts, we'll survey in the beginning if that's needed. :)

We're planning to go through a series of code labs revolving around the March Madness basketball game series. The labs involve some machine learning, starting from 0 knowledge and introducing Big Query or SQL. The follow-up labs would move towards machine learning and enhance the prediction model.

I encourage everyone to bring their own device and follow the code labs with me. No previous knowledge is needed. The device does not need to be powerful, because we'll access all cloud services through the browser. Also: there will be no charge due to special support to perform the cloud experiments.

Local developer and Root Access Hackerspace member Parrish Sims will give a lecture on GoLang to conclude our event before we raffle off our prizes.

We'll provide lunch and snacks, and there will be a raffle at the end.
Csaba returned from Cloud Next 19 with some swag! A Google Home Mini and a Google Hub!

Please keep in mind that we'll meet at Root Access Hackerspace and not Bitwise.
